{
  "step": 6,
  "title": "Take Back Control",
  "startFrame": 8258,
  "endFrame": 10415,
  "componentPath": "src/visuals/Generated_TakeBackControl.tsx",
  "transcriptSegment": "This isn't about becoming an A I purist or rejecting helpful tools. It's about maintaining the cognitive flexibility that makes you valuable as a developer. When A I inevitably fails or hallucinates or gives you deprecated solutions, you need those problem-solving muscles to still work.\n\nThe developers who will thrive in an A I-dominated future aren't the ones who can prompt engineer the best. They're the ones who can still think through problems independently when they need to. They're the ones whose brains haven't completely outsourced reasoning to external systems.\n\nDelete your A I shortcuts right now. Not permanently, just for today. Set a ten-minute timer and tackle your next coding problem without reaching for assistance. Your brain will resist this change, but that resistance is exactly the proof that you need to do it.\n\nThe goal isn't to eliminate A I from your workflow. It's to make sure you're choosing to use it, instead of being compelled to use it. Start building that friction today, before your problem-solving ability completely atrophies.",
